76561198118038977,Recommended,214510,29260861,Posted: 14 January,all,maryaha,"I've played a few Lego games. Harry Potter part I and II, lego star wars (complete edition) and clone wars, lego batman I and II (have the III), lego movie and lego superheroes (or something like that). So I'm not a newbie to Lego games. And yeah, I still love them to bits.Lego Lord of the Rings brings us the open world that I had seen previously in lego movie, lego harry potter and lego superheroes. Lego Star Wars has a somewhat open world, but not like this.Lego Lord of the Rings has one thing I did not like though. I like to be able to do missions and play with the charactes I've already unlocked in the free world. So I won't get tired of only doing story based missions. In Lego Lord of the Rings you can only play in the open world with the characters you have. For example, when I finish a mission with Legolas and Frodo I can only play with them until I do the next mission. Even if previously I was playing with Legolas, Frodo and Sam, if Sam for some reason disappears as that mission ends, I can't play with him. That annoyed me a little bit.It took me 9 hours to finish the missions (I did spend some time trying to get some bricks). Lego Lord of the Rings has the usual 10 minikits, has a ""blueprint"" that you must get in each mission and has 3 ""items"" you must also get in each mission.In the open world you can get bricks by completing races, getting to tricky places with some characters and do some quests for characters that you'll give you bricks or red bricks. The ""quests"" also exist in Lego Superheroes and somewhat in Lego Movie.Overall I liked this game like I do with every lego games. I wasn't too familiar with the story (I've seen one movie and am currently reading the books) and I liked it. I didn't think it had as much humour as the previous Lego games I've played but I did like it.And yeah, of course I'll buy another lego game when it is 4.99 again."
