,Recommended,214510,2626429,"Posted: 29 November, 2012",all,Vitamin ω «Expired Tomato»,"LEGO The Lord of the Rings is the classic tale we all know and love set to prop comedy and Louis Armstrong's seminal hit ""Blue Yodel No. 9 (Standing on the Corner)"". All the major beats of the classic teleplay are present: young Frondo Baggins is left to care for his uncle's estate after uncle Bilbo announces his retirement from the LAPD. However, the wise wizard Gonald realizes that a piece of confiscated bling Bilbo passed on to Frondo is in fact The Ring, and sets him off on a quest with his gardener Rudy.However, Frondo is situatied somewhere in the back of the title card for the game, and the story does not truly begin until reaching the elven city of San d'Oria, where Viggo Mortensen and a young Jimmy Connelly (stunningly rendered in LEGO form thanks to advancing mocap technology) join the group. Many trials and tribulations await our heroes, not the least of which trials and tribulations await our heroes, not the least of which the mad Gallum.If you've played one LEGO game, you know what to expect. LEGO The The Lord of the Rings ups the ante by introducing a basic questing and crafting system, as well as an inventory management system that puts the likes of the Resident Evil series to shame. Many medieval stand-ins appear for similar elements in other Legos games: minikit pieces become treasure chests, gold bricks become mithril (used for crafting and the exclusive one million dollar cash prize Traveler's Tales is running), and red bricks become red bricks.The LEGO Lord of the Rings takes the idea of an open world, first attempted in LEGO The Batman 2, and tweaks it in an interesting way. The hub world is in fact a completely explorable LEGO The Middle Earth, complete with side objectives. While the normal level-by-level gameplay occurs in the same static camera layout we've all come to enjoy, these little breaks between levels are a nice median between the tiny hubs of elder lego games and the huge, yet dull, world of LEGO Batman 2.Traveler's Tales has opted to pull dialogue straight from the movies for this game, which makes sense because they ultimately do not have the budget to bring on amazing, well-paid and respected actors like John Rhys-Davies and that guy who looks like a ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ Paulie Shore. Not only does this make the dialgoue volume slightly inconsistent, but it also creates interesting scenarios, like that part where Boromir dies like a ♥♥♥♥♥ being voiced with all the seriousness it deserves, while portraying a LEGO man dying of a banana to the chest.The game supports local co-operative play, which is also a staple feature of The LEGO games. The games are fairly simple to pick up and play, and provided you don't play with some♥♥♥♥♥♥who keeps wanting to kill you it's sure to be a good time. The game also splits the screen if the two players stray too far from each other, which demonstrates the amazing power of the Cell. Just don't play with your ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ younger cousin, because at some points in the game the two players control two different aspects of the same scene, and he's not going to get anywhere if you aren't there holding his hand.In conclusion, LEGO the Lord of The Rings does not disappoint, but that's only because it's impossible to set the bar for these types of games too high to behin with, and any attempt the game makes to surpass the bar is worthy of praise. Buy this game for something fun to do with friends over the weekend. Just don't invite the sperglord who loves Lord of the Rings, because I swear to God Kyle nobody gives a♥♥♥♥♥♥if this isn't a 1:1 reproduction of the movie we're just trying to have a ♥♥♥♥ing good time."
