76561198031697588,Recommended,214510,14300023,"Posted: 2 February, 2015",all,Slambojones,"The last Lego game I played was..... LEGO Star Wars II: The Original Trilogy in 2006.Being a huge Star Wars fan and a LEGO fan I had to check it out. I really enjoyed the Star Wars nostalga and all the LEGO humour. Being a Lord of the Rings fan as well I decided to grab this game during the most recent sale. I have been playing it with my girlfriend, and we just finished the story of the first movie in the series. It is an excellent game for two people to sit down and couch co-op.A caution to those who do not have controllers to use with the PC. This game is extremely hard to play on the keyboard, especially with two people! You will want to have two compatable controllers because where this games shines is in it's two-player co-op. Tonnes of LEGO LOTR characters to choose from as you often travel with a party of five or more through middleearth.I Love this game, the humour is great, the storytelling is spot on, and the collecting just never stops. If you want to play as any of your favourite  LOTR Hero's or Villains this game is for you. The Learning curve is quite simple and gameplay runs smoothly.The split screen on Co-op took a little while to get used to but once you do the game is great. Don't expect too much of a gameplay challenge as it is pretty easy, you don't lose lives just LEGO studs (money to purchase characters and items ""in game"").Where this games' challenge lies is in its treasure/loot hunting. The Levels are littered with puzzles and secrets that you require multiple different LOTR characters abilities to unlock. This makes replaying levels with new characters you unlock essential for having a complete experience.Don't shy away from this game if you have more than one person and require some two player console style fun, Get out of your Hobbit hole and whip around with some little LEGO Hobbits in a somewhat freeroaming LEGO Middleearth."
