76561197992538904,Not Recommended,214510,15207067,"Posted: 4 April, 2015",all,Yurtle the Turtle,"I really, really wish I could like this game. While I might not be the biggest LOTR fan there is, this game doesn't skimp on the story - it makes light of certain elements that kids might find a little distressing, but this isn't exactly a game designed for mature themes. It's lego, after all.The controls are adequate at best, and downright appauling at worst. You would need to bind your own keys from the default arrow keys and number pad (numbers 2 to 5, no idea who thought that was a good idea). I - for the most part - played it with a 360 controller, and bar a little ineptitude from my part, I had little issues with the controls. What makes it downright appauling then? If you have a 360 controller as player 1, and player 2 hops in on the keyboard, it isn't possible for player 2 to hop out, while player 1 can. Admittedly this has nothing to do with the controls, when you attempt to customise the keyboard controls after being forced to get rid of the controller and wanting to continue to play with something usable, player 1 now has no input. Pressing any button on the keyboard (including esc) will try to assign player 1's controller to that, but as player 2 is using it, it won't keep it. Trying to re-introduce the controller wont' help. I've pressed every button on both keyboard and controller, and onyl been able to get away from it by force quitting the game.As for character controls, the game is fine, except during the platforming elements. Or maybe I just happened to find one really, really bad one when looking for mythril blocks near Mt. Doom. It's bad enough to make half-life platforming look good.The graphics are okay, until you turn off depth-of-field and motion-blur, then they're actually quite pretty, and at least you can see stuff in the distance with it off.The comedy is as it is with all other lego games - slapstick and visual. It doesn't deviate from the story at all, so beyond silly disguises, or someone being hit over the head with something else, there aren't going to be too many giggles.To round this off - if you like lego, go play with lego. If you like lego games, you might like this one, but I'd suggest something else; this is easily the worst lego game I've played. If you like LOTR, then you might want to give this a miss. If you love LOTR or have kids who are into it, you might have some enjoyment from it."
