76561197972142968,Not Recommended,214510,14466857,"Posted: 14 February, 2015",all,Chiken_Sammich,"Lego LotR is everything you'd expect from the digital Lego franchise. This is an excellent retelling of a story we're all familiar with, laced with kid friendly humor. This is the staple of the series & TT Games delivers. However, this entry into the Lego series is problematic.Platforming is TERRIBLE. Most notibly are spots where you are forced to do the balance beam jumps. There seem to be force fields in the air that stop you from jumping far enough or into the right spot. you will repeatedly fall into the water on these sections & have to repeat the whole set of jumps over again.The stage ""Osgiliath"" is extremely buggy. The Ents will randomly rocket up into the air because of their shoddy clipping with the ground. There is a pit where if you get too close with an ent. He will go into a minute long trance & just walk toward it. The thunderous footsteps of the ents changes to clicks when the ent has both Pippin & Merry in possession. When the ent attempted to rip down the dam wall at the end of the map, the game seized all control & all I was permitted to do was change between the hobbits.On the stage ""Cirith Ungol"" there is a bug that will not allow you to trade items, between characters. If you happen to pick up 2 helmets or 2 armors with 1 character. You will be forced to restart the section.Basically this is an ok game, but it's not up to snuff. Glad I bought it on discount. I recommend you do the same if you're considering this."
,Not Recommended,214510,9841402,"Posted: 17 April, 2014",all,Azundris,"I don't think I've ever taken such an instant seething hatred to a game as I did to some of the Lego ones currently on sale. Consistently getting 70+ % scores in reviews, utilizing popular franchises so you know in advance what to expect, and promising co-op, what could possibly go wrong?First off, Lego LotR does not recognize my mouse. And no, I'm not talking about game-play yet, I'm dropped into a game where you cannot even operate the menus with the mouse. My 360 controller doesn't seem to do anything, either. I google it. No, it's not a bug or configuration hiccup, the mouse is not supported. At all. This is a classic example of ""You could've researched this, but because the notion seems so insane, you never thought to.""On the upside, you can use the controller once you've told the game that that's what you want. Using the keyboard.At which point you may notice that there are two columns for control, player 1 and 2. A dark sense of foreboding descends upon you. You shop around the options, and sure enough, there is no online play. In all fairness, this has a degree of user error to it, as the steam description plainly says, ""local co-op"", but since e.g. Lego Star Wars had online play and most reviews you'll read don't specifically mention that this game doesn't, just ""co-op"", ""I played this with my kids,"" etc., there's certainly room for misunderstanding, so I'm warning you now.The opening cinematics have a forced-funny moment or two, but given the presumed audience, I'm not sure you can blame them for trying to make things more child-accessible, except that I had a couple of ""I'm not sure this would make much sense unless you've read the book/watched the movie anyway"" moments, so at that point you already need to have decided the undiluted version isn't ""too dark"" for your spawn. (Either way, you do essentially start off playing Isildur, who is then force-killed by plot requirements ten minutes later, so what are we even talking about here?)Perhaps unsurprisingly, the game immediately drops you into an uninteresting fight against minions and finally Sauron. The game doesn't exactly tell you what to do, but not having spent your life under a rock, you aim to cut off the dark lord's finger to get on with it. Which meant battling not so much Sauron, but the controls — I know this is probably aimed at children, but does it have to feel like that game where you're supposed to eat a candy bar with knife and fork wearing huge oven mitts? The directional controls were the most unprecise it's ever been my misfortune to suffer. Strangely, the dark lord seemed to have the same issue, because we spent 10 minutes bumping into each other and swinging our weapons around without inflicting any noticeable degree of damage on each other.That's all I can say about the directional controls, except that the camera ones aren't much better. In the opening scenes, an angle is forced on you, which you can change by a handful degrees either way. Later on, you fortunately get full rotation, but turning the camera still feels slow and laborious like pushing around a boulder.The challenge of the opening mainly consisted of picking the right character for a task (""it's not like you can't jump up there, it's that you can jump there as Isildur, it looks like Elrond does the same jump, but he'll succeed"", ""it's not like you can't destroy that, you just have to pick the character with the right sword"", etc). And yeah, you may have to read the character names to pick the right bearded and helmeted Lego head.At some point, I got sufficiently frustrated with the controls that I essentially switched to finding new ways of killing myself on Mt Doom (fell off the cliff, fell in the lava, etc.), which at first glance didn't seem to have any ill effects — outside of the minifig exploding into its parts, I mean. It's not so much that you ""lose a life"", it's that you lose gold, cos our guy Isildur is constantly looting stuff as he goes along. This gold is apparently later used to unlock new characters to play or something, which they allude to in an interstitial screen that came and went so fast I wasn't sure (I'd read that you can choose a character or even create one in the Hobbit house, so I was anxious to get there. Of course, that option was not offered, so I don't know whether you first have to complete some quests, or what.).So, yeah, you know why the minifig's hands look like that? Because they've given the lego computer games all their thumbs down.tl;dr Don't impulse-buy this, despite the sale. Research very, very carefully, much more so than with ""normal"" games, just reading a few reviews on metacritic can be vastly misleading. If unsure at all, Do. Not. Buy."
