,Not Recommended,214510,9867351,"Posted: 18 April, 2014",all,ripentaro,"I have been a fan of the Lego games since the initial run of Star Wars titles. As such, I was well aware of the minor problems with controls and camera that have always been prepared to deal with them in each new Traveller's Tale title but the gameplay and glitch issues make this game feel incredibly slapdash. There are other issues beyond these that I take issue with but as they are secondary they shall wait till later in my review. Firstly glitches. You don't notice them early on but as you start to explore the HUB world more they become more redolent. You will fall through the world on an occasional basis but this can be fixed by instant travelling to a location. the more crippling factor is the broken collision detection for both characters and objects. Frequently you will find your character floating uselessly in the air. Floating objects are a more nefarious as they will render push and pull block puzzles unsolvable. These kind of glitches are so frequent as to render it impossible to believe that they would not have been caught by game testers had a proper  quality control been done. This leaves the game feeling, in spite of its graphical quality, extremely unpolished.Now on to gameplay. The controls are terrible. Direction feels imprecise and button response is indecisive. Buttons very often do not respond as desired, such as when holding the Y button is supposed to bring up the character select but instead just swaps you with the second player (extremely annoying when playing co-op). At other times they simply do not respond at all, such as the case of the extremely flaky jump button. This, paired with the vague directional input, leads to much cursing in what is essentially a platformer. Much of the challenge in this game arises not from clever puzzles but from the player fighting the controls.Another problem in gameplay are the design choices. Many quest-givers (is that a word?) are in hard to reach locations making just the act of turning in a quest an annoyance. More annoying are the menus. This is illustrated most by the constructable items. In the game you can build certain items that allow you to mimic one character's powers on another. This is rendered superfluous by the fact that you have to navigate 2 menus to equip the item each time so that it is simply faster to search one menu to find the character with the requisite power. Every time something requires doing you might as well just whip out Samwise The Swiss Army Knife of Middle Earth.Alright, the finale: Story. But this follows the story of the movies, right? That should be a good thing, right?... Actually, no. Here's why. There is no freedom to deviate from the scripts of the movies as they are married to using the film's audio. Part of the enjoyment of the Star Wars and Indiana Jones games where their ability to deviate from the source materials in order to better facilitate gameplay or to make jokes that could not be done with the source dialogue in place. Yes, there are added jokes in this game but as they cannot change or add dialogue many of them feel weird and out of place, especially in a movie that maintains a serious tone in almost all of its dialogue. The original audio also prevents them from adding story sequences that weren't in the movie, for example an added Tom Bombadil/ Old Willow Level would have made a welcome addition but, as there was no dialogue for this they couldn't. This issue of the audio was initially what steered me away from the game until the recent sale, mostly because of the serious tone of the story. I was not really interested in seeing these performances being juxtaposed with silly sight gags. My fear was realized and many of the jokes feel out of place or will leave you saying, ""Oh, that's just wrong."" Should have listened to my doubts. At least it was only five bucks."
,Recommended,214510,31166473,Posted: 15 April,all,󠀡󠀡󠀡󠀡󠀡󠀡󠀡Dragnr,You wil not step on any of it.
,Not Recommended,214510,9510429,"Posted: 17 March, 2014",all,ambershee,"Mildly amusing and a fairly entertaining romp, but there are many issues that let this game down. Overall, it's a very sloppy port to PC.1) It's a PC game that doesn't support the mouse, despite several game mechanics being ideally built for it - for example aiming ranged attacks brings up a reticule that must be placed over a target. The game does not support the Playstation 3 pad, so if you want to play it, I'd have to recommend picking up a 360 controller.2) It's buggy. Characters will frequently get stuck in walls and other such similar annoyances. Thankfully if you move far enough away, they'll teleport behind you when you're not looking, but this isn't always an option. Mercifully, I've not found myself unable to continue at any point. Rendering errors are frequent - and I've found myself unable to continue past the Nazgul attack in the moors, as some sort of ground overlay is floating around in the z-axis meaning I can't actually see the gameplay area. From what I gather, the console version of the game have been patched, but the PC version has been neglected and abandoned. Reading online also indicates that there are bugs related to white blocks that can potentially make it impossible to finish the game.3) The overall design isn't great and the game has it's problems. Some of the character interplay towards the mid-game is nice and it may get better later (though I may potentially never find out as I'm unable to continue), but the level design is shockingly poor. The majority of the game is entirely linear, including the puzzle sections which have components that illogically have to be completed in a certain order rendering the puzzle section little more than a waste of time as you go through the required motions. Large parts of the game seem to take place on hills and slopes, but the player is tasked with collecting studs which are represented with rigid bodies - as a result you'll spend a lot of time chasing them down hills to collect them, only finding they have rolled into water or off a cliff and are therefore unobtainable. Some levels have too many playable characters - one level has the entire Fellowship of nine characters, which makes selecting the correct character a chore - it doesn't even fit on the character wheel any more. Some of the character icons, particularly those of the hobbits, are difficult to discern from one another, compounding the frustration. In some cases areas of the levels are enclosed and too small (such as structures in Rivendell), meaning that the camera is obscured by outside walls of the structure, meaning you cannot see what you are doing. Lastly, some of the lighting and choice of colour palette can make some things in the environment very difficult to discern, particularly during levels that take place at night.Overall the game is entertaining, but frustrating due to issues, and I cannot recommend it."
