,Recommended,214510,9200538,"Posted: 20 February, 2014",all,King James,"As a fan of the LEGO game series, I enjoyed LEGO LoTR. If you've never played a LEGO game, though, I'm not sure if this is the one to start with unless you're a big huge fan of LoTR. One of the things I've enjoyed about the LEGO games is the anarchic sense of humor and the willingness to lovingly goof around with the source material. However, LEGO LoTR is oddly restrained. Maybe it's because it not only follows the story of the film series, but uses actual audio clips in doing so, that the sense of playing around with the material isn't there like it is with the other LEGO games, such as the silent Star Wars and Indiana Jones games. Maybe it was an intentional design choice. The humor is still there, but it's just not there in the same laugh out loud way that previous games in the series had.Still, the game is fun to play. There's a wide range of characters, but the addition of the Mithril Treasures that allow any character to have the powers of any other character in some ways means that you won't be playing as quite so many characters in free play. Quite literally, once you've got the Mithril Treasures, you can play as a single character in Free Play and accomplish every task without switching out your character.Pretty much every character of note in the film series makes their way into the game, as well as some that only found their way into the Extended Edition footage. There's also some that never made it out of pre-production, like the love-him-or-hate-him Tom Bombadil. I am not a giant LoTR fanboy but I consider myself decently familiar with the source material both in film and book form, and even I'll admit that there were several characters I had to go to an LoTR wiki to remember who they were. The film's locations are also recreated on a small scale but are instantly recognizable. The details are appreciated especially as the game has an extensive overworld with a lot of secrets and quests to complete.If you're a veteran of the LEGO games looking to get your fix, or a big huge fan of LoTR (particularly the film series), I'd recommend this title. If you've never played a LEGO game, you may want to start with another title in the series to figure out whether they're your cup of tea before you pick this one up."
