76561198065983450,Not Recommended,214510,35458372,Posted: 3 October,all,sourshot,"If you are a fan of the Lego Star Wars games, you probably won't enjoy this game. For some reason it has an open world element without any kind of centralized hub.  The level design is okay at best, and boring at worst. There are two boss fights: shoot a thing with arrows until you are allowed to mash X and watch your character do something cool, and big invulnerable guy hits the ground and sends a damaging line to hit you, wait him out until he becomes vulnerable repeat. Most of the levels basically play themselves by giving you giant arrows to every objective you need, and giving a massive rotating gold border to things you need to throw rocks or shoot arrows at. Some of the platforming is decent, though there are quite a few places where you can get stuck, or something loses the ability to be interacted with, forcing you to restart the game. Button prompts, every single action you take you will get a button prompt, in boss fights you can usually press the wrong button and it will do the input anyway. All of the voice work is taken directly from the movies, and often isn't mixed very well, which gives the game a very cheap feeling. As I mentioned previously there are some severe scripting errors that can force a lot of backtracking if you're unlucky. A lot of the levels feel underdesigned probably because a lot of time had to go into the sparse world that you travel between levels. If you want a Lego game that feels both finished and has stellar level design, check out either of the first two Lego Star Wars games. 4/10"
